I am a School Without Walls alum.... graduated in 2008, so from 2004 on, this deli was a go to. I looovveed their BLTs and would get it on Pumpernickel or Rye with provolone. Some years passed and I no longer frequented the area, but anytime I wanted a BLT, I would crave the BLT from this place. I started working in Georgetown recently and found myself craving a BLT. I foolishly ordered from a different deli and was SORELY disappointed. Because my craving wasn't satisfied, about 2 weeks later, I made a trip just to see if this deli was still open and was beyond thrilled to see that they were! I promptly stood in line to order my BLT. This time, I got even fancier and put avocado on my sandwich. The layers of bacon were as thick and gorgeous as I remembered and they were also generous with the avocado. I'm ashamed to say how much joy that first bite brought to my mouth/ soul. It was a messy lunch but OMG it was sooo worth it. I'll definitely be back and highly recommend this place to anyone looking for a good deli sandwich.

The crowd advances through GW Deli in what should be considered the ultimate demonstration of chaotic efficiency. Chilled drinks, baked goods, and snack items line the narrow aisle. If you see something you like, be decisive. There's no going back for it once you move forward. When you reach the counter, the time for decision making has already passed. This is a proletarian delicatessen-- not some bougie 1950's soda shoppe. Order with confidence and you will be rewarded with a culinary tour de force worthy of "Lunch atop a Skyscraper." The pastrami on rye with everything is life changing.
